<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="66" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name, 
<taxonomicName box="[583,683,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cabrerae">
<emphasis box="[583,683,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">cabrerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, pays homage to Nora Cabrera (Museo de La Plata, La Plata, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,267,295,320]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Argentina</collectingCountry>
), an expert who dedicated her life to the study of Neotropical chrysomelids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="66" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Remarks.</emphasis>
Many of the members of 
<taxonomicName box="[602,725,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[602,725,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Yingaresca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have four tubercles on each elytron: two basal—one next to the humerus and another on the disc, close to the scutellum – and two apical, one external and another more on the internal face. Despite the arbitrariness of the division of 
<taxonomicName box="[789,912,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[789,912,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Yingaresca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
into groups of species (
<bibRefCitation author="Wilcox" box="[1183,1332,404,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="70" refString="Wilcox, J. A. (1971) Coleopterorum Catalogus. Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae. 78 (1). 2 nd Edition. s' - Gravenhage, W. Junk, 220 pp." type="book" year="1971">
Wilcox 
<number box="[1273,1332,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" value="1971.0">1971</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and the fact that there are no descriptions, to date, defining such groups, we can include 
<taxonomicName box="[1044,1274,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cabrerae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1044,1274,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Yingaresca cabrerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1280,1369,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1280,1369,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, even though preliminarily, among the 
<taxonomicName box="[521,644,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[521,644,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Yingaresca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the group 
<taxonomicName box="[798,890,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Yingaresca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis box="[798,890,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since it shares an x-shaped pronotum and more evident elytral tubercles. Besides the colored elytral pattern, the new species is the only one in the genus that bears an elevated and conspicuously triangular apical tubercle.
</paragraph>
